EDTA (Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid) functions as a high-affinity heavy metal chelator in neuroprotection and neurotoxicology research. Its primary mechanism involves trapping toxic divalent and trivalent cations (such as lead, cadmium, aluminum, and free iron) that accumulate in brain tissues like the hypothalamus, preventing them from driving chronic microglial activation and subsequent neuroinflammation. [1, 2, 3, 4("https://www.researchgate.net/post/Protein_extraction_with_without_EDTA")] ; [1("https://www.researchgate.net/publication/353752965_Effects_of_Vitamin_C_and_Dimethylsulfoxide_Dmso_on_Neuro-Behaviour_Apoptosis_and_oxidative_stress_in_ischaemic_stroke_induced_rats")]\
